---
interface Props { data: any; }
const { data } = Astro.props;
const INSP = {
  one: { csvLines: data.inspector.oneSite.csvLines, jsonText: data.inspector.oneSite.jsonText },
  all: { csvLines: data.inspector.allSites.csvLines, jsonText: data.inspector.allSites.jsonText },
};
const SC = data.selfCheckReplies;
---

<!-- 0 · COVER -->
<section class="frame cover show" data-frame="0">
  <div class="cover-left">
    <div class="step-eyebrow">JSON and Data Interchange</div>
    <h1>The format AI tools pass data around in</h1>
    <p class="lead">If a CSV is a flat table, JSON is what you reach for the moment your data has shape inside it. It looks scarier than it is — once you see the pattern, it opens up a whole layer of how AI tools talk to each other.</p>
    <div class="scene">
      <div class="scene-row"><span class="k">What this is</span><span>A plain look at JSON, the format AI tools and integrations pass data around in.</span></div>
      <div class="scene-row"><span class="k">Why you'd care</span><span>The moment you touch chatbots, integrations, or APIs, you meet JSON. Reading it removes a lot of guesswork.</span></div>
      <div class="scene-row"><span class="k">What you'll do</span><span>See the same visitor data as a CSV, as JSON, and as a visual tree, and watch which one holds shape the others cannot.</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="signpost">
      <b>The shape of the next thirteen minutes.</b> Six short steps. You'll compare the formats first, then we'll name the anatomy. You can open a <b>"new to this?"</b> panel anywhere you want more grounding.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="cover-right">
    <div class="videoframe" role="img" aria-label="Orientation video, 75 seconds">
      <div class="playdot"></div>
      <div class="vlabel">Why this matters</div>
      <div class="vtime">75 seconds</div>
      <div class="vplaceholder">video · Vimeo embed</div>
    </div>
    <div class="promise"><b>By the end:</b> you'll be able to open a JSON file without panicking, read what it holds, and understand why so many AI tools use this format.</div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 1 · SEE IT FOR YOURSELF -->
<section class="frame" data-frame="1">
  <div class="step-eyebrow">Step 1 of 6 · Try it first</div>
  <h2>Same data, three formats. Watch what each one can hold.</h2>
  <div class="challenge">
    <b>Your challenge:</b> switch between one site and all three sites, then step through the three views.
    <span class="lookfor">→ What to look for: in the JSON and tree views, notice how each site appears once, with its visits nested underneath. In the CSV, the site name has to repeat on every row.</span>
  </div>
  <div class="inspector">
    <div class="insp-controls">
      <div class="ctrl">
        <span class="ctrl-label">Data</span>
        <div class="toggle" role="tablist" aria-label="Choose dataset">
          <button data-set="one" class="on" role="tab" aria-selected="true"><span class="dotmark dotmark-one"></span>One site</button>
          <button data-set="all" role="tab" aria-selected="false"><span class="dotmark dotmark-all"></span>All three sites</button>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="ctrl">
        <span class="ctrl-label">View</span>
        <div class="viewtabs" role="tablist" aria-label="Choose a view">
          <button data-view="csv" class="on" role="tab" aria-selected="true">CSV</button>
          <button data-view="json" role="tab" aria-selected="false">JSON</button>
          <button data-view="tree" role="tab" aria-selected="false">Tree</button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="insp-stage">
      <div class="insp-view show" data-view="csv">
        <div class="view-cap">A flat CSV — site name repeats on every row.</div>
        <div class="raw" id="csvView43"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="insp-view" data-view="json">
        <div class="view-cap">JSON — the site appears once, with its visits nested inside.</div>
        <pre class="json-view" id="jsonView43"></pre>
      </div>
      <div class="insp-view" data-view="tree">
        <div class="view-cap">Tree diagram — the nesting structure made visible.</div>
        <div class="tree-view">
          <div class="tree-set" id="tree43one">
            <div class="tree-brace">&#123; &#125; <span class="tree-label">one record</span></div>
            <div class="tree-children">
              <div class="tree-row"><span class="tree-key">"site"</span><span class="tree-colon">:</span><span class="tree-val str">"Harbour Museum"</span></div>
              <div class="tree-row"><span class="tree-key">"type"</span><span class="tree-colon">:</span><span class="tree-val str">"museum"</span></div>
              <div class="tree-row">
                <span class="tree-key">"visits"</span><span class="tree-colon">:</span><span class="tree-arr">[ ] <span class="tree-label">3 items</span></span>
                <div class="tree-children tree-nested">
                  <div class="tree-item">&#123; <span class="tree-k2">"date"</span>: <span class="tree-val str">"2025-06-01"</span>, <span class="tree-k2">"visitors"</span>: <span class="tree-val num">342</span>, <span class="tree-k2">"revenue_gbp"</span>: <span class="tree-val num">1710</span> &#125;</div>
                  <div class="tree-item">&#123; <span class="tree-k2">"date"</span>: <span class="tree-val str">"2025-06-02"</span>, <span class="tree-k2">"visitors"</span>: <span class="tree-val num">389</span>, <span class="tree-k2">"revenue_gbp"</span>: <span class="tree-val num">1945</span> &#125;</div>
                  <div class="tree-item">&#123; <span class="tree-k2">"date"</span>: <span class="tree-val str">"2025-06-03"</span>, <span class="tree-k2">"visitors"</span>: <span class="tree-val num">401</span>, <span class="tree-k2">"revenue_gbp"</span>: <span class="tree-val num">2005</span> &#125;</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="tree-set" id="tree43all" style="display:none">
            <div class="tree-brace">[ ] <span class="tree-label">3 sites</span></div>
            <div class="tree-children">
              <div class="tree-row">
                <span class="tree-arr">&#123; &#125; <span class="tree-label">Harbour Museum</span></span>
                <div class="tree-children tree-nested">
                  <div class="tree-row"><span class="tree-key">"site"</span><span class="tree-colon">:</span><span class="tree-val str">"Harbour Museum"</span></div>
                  <div class="tree-row"><span class="tree-key">"visits"</span><span class="tree-colon">:</span><span class="tree-arr">[ ] <span class="tree-label">2 visits</span></span></div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="tree-row">
                <span class="tree-arr">&#123; &#125; <span class="tree-label">Old Lighthouse</span></span>
                <div class="tree-children tree-nested">
                  <div class="tree-row"><span class="tree-key">"site"</span><span class="tree-colon">:</span><span class="tree-val str">"Old Lighthouse"</span></div>
                  <div class="tree-row"><span class="tree-key">"visits"</span><span class="tree-colon">:</span><span class="tree-arr">[ ] <span class="tree-label">2 visits</span></span></div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="tree-row">
                <span class="tree-arr">&#123; &#125; <span class="tree-label">Cliff Gardens</span></span>
                <div class="tree-children tree-nested">
                  <div class="tree-row"><span class="tree-key">"site"</span><span class="tree-colon">:</span><span class="tree-val str">"Cliff Gardens"</span></div>
                  <div class="tree-row"><span class="tree-key">"visits"</span><span class="tree-colon">:</span><span class="tree-arr">[ ] <span class="tree-label">2 visits</span></span></div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="askrow">
      <span class="q">Can this format hold each site's details once, with its visits nested underneath?</span>
      <span class="a" id="askAnswer43"></span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 2 · WHAT YOU JUST SAW -->
<section class="frame" data-frame="2">
  <div class="step-eyebrow">Step 2 of 6 · The idea</div>
  <h2>JSON: records of name-and-value pairs, with lists in square brackets.</h2>
  <div class="concept-visual">
    <div class="json-anatomy">
      <div class="ja-line"><span class="ja-brace">&#123;</span></div>
      <div class="ja-line ja-indent">
        <span class="ja-key">"site"</span><span class="ja-colon">: </span><span class="ja-str">"Harbour Museum"</span><span class="ja-comma">,</span>
        <span class="ja-note">← a name-and-value pair</span>
      </div>
      <div class="ja-line ja-indent">
        <span class="ja-key">"visits"</span><span class="ja-colon">: </span><span class="ja-bracket">[</span>
        <span class="ja-note">← square bracket opens a list</span>
      </div>
      <div class="ja-line ja-indent2">
        <span class="ja-brace">&#123; </span><span class="ja-key">"date"</span><span class="ja-colon">: </span><span class="ja-str">"2025-06-01"</span>, <span class="ja-key">"visitors"</span><span class="ja-colon">: </span><span class="ja-num">342</span><span class="ja-brace"> &#125;</span>
        <span class="ja-note">← one record inside the list</span>
      </div>
      <div class="ja-line ja-indent"><span class="ja-bracket">]</span></div>
      <div class="ja-line"><span class="ja-brace">&#125;</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p class="takeline"><b>That's most of JSON.</b> Curly braces wrap one record (the name-and-value pairs). Square brackets wrap a list. Records can nest inside records. A CSV can only go one level deep — every value is a cell in a flat grid. JSON can go as many levels deep as the data needs.</p>
  <details class="disclosure">
    <summary><span class="chev">▶</span>New to this? Start here<span class="tag">30-second grounding</span></summary>
    <div class="body">
      In JSON, <b>curly braces { }</b> wrap one thing (a record, a site, an event). Inside them are <b>name-and-value pairs</b> — like a form: <code>"visitors": 455</code>. <b>Square brackets [ ]</b> wrap a list of things. <b>Quotes</b> go around text values; <b>numbers and true/false</b> need no quotes. The nesting — records inside records inside lists — is what lets JSON hold shapes a flat CSV cannot. You read and check JSON far more often than you write it.
    </div>
  </details>
</section>

<!-- 3 · QUICK CHECK -->
<section class="frame" data-frame="3">
  <div class="step-eyebrow">Step 3 of 6 · Quick check</div>
  <h2>Read one line of JSON before we move on.</h2>
  <p class="sub">In a JSON file you see this line: <span style="font-family:var(--mono);color:var(--navy);font-size:13px">"sites": [ {"{...}"}, {"{...}"}, {"{...}"} ]</span>. What does it tell you?</p>
  <div class="options" id="checkOptions">
    <button class="opt" data-correct="false"><span class="key">A</span><span>There is one site, described by three fields.</span></button>
    <button class="opt" data-correct="true"><span class="key">B</span><span>There is a list of three sites, each its own record.</span></button>
    <button class="opt" data-correct="false"><span class="key">C</span><span>There is one record with three nested lists inside it.</span></button>
  </div>
  <div class="reveal" id="checkReveal">
    <b>It's B.</b> The square brackets mean "this is a list", and each set of curly braces inside is one site's record. A list of three records is one of the most common shapes in JSON, and once you recognise the pattern — <span style="font-family:var(--mono)">[ {"{...}"}, {"{...}"} ]</span> — you can read it anywhere.
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 4 · CHOOSE YOUR APPROACH -->
<section class="frame" data-frame="4">
  <div class="step-eyebrow">Step 4 of 6 · Choose your approach</div>
  <h2>Tools for reading and checking JSON.</h2>
  <table class="tools">
    <thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Cost</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td class="tool">JSONLint</td><td><span class="pill free">Free</span></td><td>Checks a JSON file is valid and points to the exact line if it is not. The first thing to reach for when JSON "won't load".</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tool">JSON Crack</td><td><span class="pill free">Free</span></td><td>Turns JSON into a visual tree so the structure is obvious at a glance. Good for understanding an unfamiliar file.</td></tr>
      <tr><td class="tool">Browser console</td><td><span class="pill free">Free</span></td><td>Lets you peek at the JSON that any website or tool is sending and receiving. Useful once you are curious about how your tools talk.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p class="neutral-note">These tools read and check JSON; you rarely need to write it by hand. Most JSON you encounter was generated by a tool and can be checked or converted by another.</p>
</section>

<!-- 5 · YOUR TURN -->
<section class="frame" data-frame="5">
  <div class="step-eyebrow">Step 5 of 6 · Your turn</div>
  <h2>Read a JSON file and convert it.</h2>
  <div class="turn-grid">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>1 · The sample file</h3>
      <p class="sub" style="margin-bottom:11px">Download the Harbour Museum visitor data as JSON. Open it in a text editor and skim the structure before you paste the prompt.</p>
      <div class="row-actions"><button class="btn primary" id="dlBtn">Download visitor-record.json</button></div>
      <p class="sub" style="margin-top:11px;font-size:12.5px">Then try with a JSON export from one of your own tools.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>2 · The prompt to paste</h3>
      <div class="promptbox" id="promptText">Here is a JSON file. In plain English, tell me what data it holds and how it is organised. Then convert it to a simple CSV table I could open in a spreadsheet, and explain what gets lost when you flatten it.</div>
      <div class="row-actions"><button class="btn" id="copyBtn">Copy prompt</button></div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <ol class="steps">
    <li>Open your AI tool, attach <b>visitor-record.json</b>, and paste the prompt.</li>
    <li>Read its description of the structure. Does it match what you saw in the tree view?</li>
    <li>Try converting one of your own spreadsheets to JSON with AI, then back again.</li>
  </ol>
  <div class="selfcheck">
    <div class="q">How did it go?</div>
    <div class="sc-btns">
      <button class="btn" data-sc="worked">It worked</button>
      <button class="btn" data-sc="partly">Partly</button>
      <button class="btn" data-sc="stuck">I got stuck</button>
    </div>
    <div class="sc-reply" id="scReply"></div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 6 · CARRY FORWARD -->
<section class="frame" data-frame="6">
  <div class="step-eyebrow">Step 6 of 6 · Carry forward</div>
  <h2>What to take with you.</h2>
  <ul class="takeaways">
    <li>JSON is records of name-and-value pairs: curly braces wrap one record, square brackets wrap a list, and records can nest inside records.</li>
    <li>It holds shapes a flat CSV cannot — a site once, with all its visits nested underneath — which is why integrations and AI tools prefer it.</li>
    <li>You read and check JSON far more often than you write it. JSONLint is the first tool to reach for when something won't load.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="next-cards">
    <div class="next-card"><div class="nlabel">NEXT</div><div class="ntitle">4.2 Spreadsheets and CSVs</div><div class="nwhy">The flat cousin — how the two formats relate.</div></div>
    <div class="next-card"><div class="nlabel">NEXT</div><div class="ntitle">4.4 Schemas, Fields, and Clean Data</div><div class="nwhy">Giving any format rules it promises to follow.</div></div>
    <div class="next-card"><div class="nlabel">NEXT</div><div class="ntitle">1.5 APIs</div><div class="nwhy">Where JSON travels between tools — coming soon.</div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="complete-row">
    <button class="btn primary" id="completeBtn">Mark module complete</button>
    <span class="completed-msg" id="completedMsg">✓ Module complete. Progress saved.</span>
  </div>
</section>

<script is:inline define:vars={{ INSP, SC }}>
(function () {
  var mainEl = document.querySelector('.lesson[data-module-id]');
  var modId  = mainEl ? mainEl.dataset.moduleId : '';
  var PK = 'dl_progress';
  function pRead() { try { return JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(PK) || '{}'); } catch (e) { return {}; } }
  function pWrite(m) {
    try { localStorage.setItem(PK, JSON.stringify(m)); } catch (e) {}
    if (typeof window.__msWriteProgress === 'function') window.__msWriteProgress();
  }

  var currentSet  = 'one';
  var currentView = 'csv';

  function esc(t) { return t.replace(/&/g,'&amp;').replace(/</g,'&lt;').replace(/>/g,'&gt;'); }

  function highlightJSON(str) {
    return esc(str)
      .replace(/"([^"]+)"(\s*:)/g, '<span class="jk">"$1"</span>$2')
      .replace(/:\s*"([^"]*)"/g, ': <span class="jv">"$1"</span>')
      .replace(/:\s*(\d+)/g, ': <span class="jn">$1</span>')
      .replace(/([{}[\]])/g, '<span class="jb">$1</span>');
  }

  function renderCSV() {
    var lines = currentSet === 'one' ? INSP.one.csvLines : INSP.all.csvLines;
    var html = '';
    lines.forEach(function (line, i) {
      var txt = esc(line).replace(/,/g, '<span class="comma">,</span>');
      var cls = i === 0 ? ' hdr' : '';
      html += '<div class="raw-line' + cls + '">' + txt + '</div>';
    });
    document.getElementById('csvView43').innerHTML = html;
  }

  function renderJSON() {
    var text = currentSet === 'one' ? INSP.one.jsonText : INSP.all.jsonText;
    document.getElementById('jsonView43').innerHTML = highlightJSON(text);
  }

  function renderTree() {
    var t1 = document.getElementById('tree43one');
    var t2 = document.getElementById('tree43all');
    if (t1) t1.style.display = currentSet === 'one' ? '' : 'none';
    if (t2) t2.style.display = currentSet === 'all' ? '' : 'none';
  }

  function updateConsequence() {
    var el  = document.getElementById('askAnswer43');
    if (!el) return;
    if (currentView === 'csv') {
      el.className = 'a bad'; el.textContent = 'No — site repeats on every row ✗';
    } else {
      el.className = 'a good'; el.textContent = 'Yes — site appears once, visits nested ✓';
    }
  }

  function setAll() {
    renderCSV(); renderJSON(); renderTree(); updateConsequence();
  }

  document.querySelectorAll('.toggle button').forEach(function (b) {
    b.onclick = function () {
      currentSet = b.dataset.set;
      document.querySelectorAll('.toggle button').forEach(function (x) {
        var on = x === b; x.classList.toggle('on', on); x.setAttribute('aria-selected', on ? 'true' : 'false');
      });
      setAll();
    };
  });

  document.querySelectorAll('.viewtabs button').forEach(function (b) {
    b.onclick = function () {
      currentView = b.dataset.view;
      document.querySelectorAll('.insp-view').forEach(function (el) {
        el.classList.toggle('show', el.dataset.view === currentView);
      });
      document.querySelectorAll('.viewtabs button').forEach(function (x) {
        var on = x === b; x.classList.toggle('on', on); x.setAttribute('aria-selected', on ? 'true' : 'false');
      });
      updateConsequence();
    };
  });

  setAll();

  var answered = false;
  document.querySelectorAll('#checkOptions .opt').forEach(function (opt) {
    opt.onclick = function () {
      if (answered) return; answered = true;
      document.querySelectorAll('#checkOptions .opt').forEach(function (o) {
        if (o.dataset.correct === 'true') o.classList.add('correct');
        else if (o === opt) o.classList.add('wrong');
        else o.classList.add('dim');
      });
      document.getElementById('checkReveal').classList.add('show');
    };
  });

  document.getElementById('dlBtn').onclick = function () {
    var a = document.createElement('a'); a.href = '/dttt/4-3/visitor-record.json'; a.download = 'visitor-record.json';
    document.body.appendChild(a); a.click(); document.body.removeChild(a);
    this.textContent = 'Downloaded ✓';
    var b = this; setTimeout(function () { b.textContent = 'Download visitor-record.json'; }, 2200);
  };

  document.getElementById('copyBtn').onclick = function () {
    var txt = document.getElementById('promptText').innerText; var b = this;
    function done() { b.textContent = 'Copied ✓'; setTimeout(function () { b.textContent = 'Copy prompt'; }, 2200); }
    if (navigator.clipboard && navigator.clipboard.writeText) navigator.clipboard.writeText(txt).then(done, done);
    else { var ta = document.createElement('textarea'); ta.value = txt; document.body.appendChild(ta); ta.select(); try { document.execCommand('copy'); } catch (e) {} document.body.removeChild(ta); done(); }
  };

  document.querySelectorAll('[data-sc]').forEach(function (b) {
    b.onclick = function () { var r = document.getElementById('scReply'); r.textContent = SC[b.dataset.sc]; r.classList.add('show'); };
  });

  document.getElementById('completeBtn').onclick = function () {
    var m = pRead(); var cur = m[modId] || { complete: false, furthest: 0 };
    m[modId] = Object.assign({}, cur, { complete: true }); pWrite(m);
    document.getElementById('completedMsg').classList.add('show'); this.disabled = true; this.textContent = 'Completed';
  };

  var prog = pRead()[modId];
  if (prog && prog.complete) {
    var msg = document.getElementById('completedMsg'); var btn = document.getElementById('completeBtn');
    if (msg) msg.classList.add('show');
    if (btn) { btn.disabled = true; btn.textContent = 'Completed'; }
  }
})();
</script>
